3	/**
4	 * detection-spec.js - the detection-spec migration (P3 Wave-2a, breach proposer layer).
5	 *
6	 * The compiled catalogue ships DUTIES AS PROSE: every record's website_obligations[] is a list of
7	 * { duty, elements[], evidence_type } where elements[] are human sentences, not machine patterns
8	 * (catalogue/README.md: "duties are prose, not regex, until a future detection migration"). This
9	 * module IS that migration. It reads the compiled catalogue at RUNTIME and derives, IN MEMORY, a
10	 * machine-checkable DetectionSpec per obligation. The packs are never touched: no pattern is written
11	 * back, nothing here edits a catalogue file (Constitution Rule 2, catalogue/packs are QA-stamped).
12	 *
13	 * A proposer PROPOSES; it never emits a finding. The DetectionSpec is the grammar a proposer runs to
14	 * turn one obligation into a breach CANDIDATE. propose.js is the only evaluator; the verifier and
15	 * adjudicator downstream turn a candidate into (or reject it from) a finding.
16	 *
17	 * ── The DetectionSpec grammar ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
18	 *   {
19	 *     record_id,        // the catalogue record id (upper-snake) this spec checks
20	 *     duty_idx,         // index into record.website_obligations[] (which duty)
21	 *     evidence_type,    // 'presence' | 'absence' | 'behavioural' | 'register' (the obligation's own)
22	 *     surface,          // 'visible_text' | 'raw_html' | 'footer' | 'register_row' | 'browser_lane'
23	 *     patterns: [ { kind, value, negation_guarded } ],
24	 *     page_class,       // the crawl page-class this on-page duty needs (coverage-contract), or null
25	 *   }
26	 *
27	 * evidence_type is the catalogue polarity, verbatim (catalogue/linters/polarity.js SEMANTIC DOCTRINE):
28	 *   - 'presence'    the duty names REQUIRED content; the site breaches when it is MISSING. propose.js
29	 *                   runs this as an ABSENCE-breach (required pattern absent across a COVERED surface),
30	 *                   artifact = coverage_proof. This is the truncation-sensitive, russell-cooke class
31	 *                   (C-024): it fires only with the coverage interlock proven.
32	 *   - 'absence'     the duty names PROHIBITED content; the site breaches when it IS PRESENT. propose.js
33	 *                   runs this as a PRESENCE-breach (prohibited pattern found in visible prose),
34	 *                   artifact = the verbatim quote. negation_guarded is true so the site's OWN compliant
35	 *                   self-declaration ("we do not treat under-18s") is not read as the prohibited claim
36	 *                   (C-048/C-060, the Botox-U18 polarity trap).
37	 *   - 'register'    proved against a pre-fetched register row (evidence/registers), surface
38	 *                   'register_row', page_class null: the crawl never gates it.
39	 *   - 'behavioural' proved by an observed browser action (evidence/browser), surface 'browser_lane',
40	 *                   page_class null.
41	 *
42	 * ── surface = evidence surface, DECLARED per rule (C-035/C-036/C-034) ────────────────────────────
43	 * A spec's surface is BOTH where propose.js detects AND where it cuts the quote, so a hit and its quote
44	 * can never disagree (C-035). The C-036 asymmetry is encoded here: a PROHIBITION ('absence') triggers on
45	 * VISIBLE prose only ('visible_text'), since a forbidden claim inside a <script> is not a public claim;
46	 * a REQUIRED MECHANISM that legitimately lives in JavaScript (a consent tool, an embedded badge) routes
47	 * to 'raw_html' so a strict visible check cannot fabricate a "missing" breach on a compliant JS control,
48	 * and since the pure EvidenceBundle is stripped text only (C-012) propose.js ABSTAINS on 'raw_html'
